Secrets Manager versus Parameter Store.

Applications need credentials at runtime, database passwords, A-P-I keys, OAuth tokens. Hard-code them in a config file and you have a leak waiting to happen. Two services hold them, and the split is rotation, cost, and size.

Secrets Manager stores credentials and gives the application a single GetSecretValue call to retrieve them. Two things make it more than a glorified key-value store. The first is rotation. A rotation Lambda runs four steps: create a new credential in the target service, update the secret value, test the new credential, and retire the old one. Built-in rotation Lambdas exist for R-D-S, that's MySQL, PostgreSQL, Oracle, SQL Server, and Aurora, plus Redshift and DocumentDB; for anything else you write a custom Lambda following the same four-step contract. Because the app reads the current secret on each connection, rotation needs no restart and no redeploy. The second is versioning: every value is versioned with staging labels, A-W-S-CURRENT and A-W-S-PENDING, so rotation can stage a new value and promote it safely.

Now the comparison. On cost, Secrets Manager is about forty cents per secret per month plus A-P-I calls, while Parameter Store is free at the Standard tier. On rotation, Secrets Manager has it built in with Lambda; Parameter Store has none, it's manual only. On encryption, Secrets Manager always uses K-M-S; Parameter Store makes it optional with the SecureString type. Secrets Manager holds up to sixty-five kilobytes and integrates natively with R-D-S managed passwords; Parameter Store tops out at four or eight kilobytes and does not.

The rule is simple. If rotation is part of the security story, database credentials, expiring A-P-I keys, OAuth secrets, use Secrets Manager. For plain, non-secret configuration, feature flags, A-R-Ns, environment names, use Parameter Store, which is free at Standard and integrates with everything. Many real architectures use both.
